9) grid-template-columns: 20% 20% 20% 20% 20%; and grid-template-rows: 20% 20% 20% 20% 20%; -> these commands create a 5*5 grid. We can change this grid to any dimension using these commands.
10) We previously defined five 20% columns with the rule grid-template-columns: 20% 20% 20% 20% 20%;. This can be simplified as grid-template-columns: repeat(5, 20%);
11) grid-template-columns doesn't just accept values in percentages, but also length units like pixels and ems. You can even mix different units together. So we can have grid-templatte-columns: 100px 3em 40%; to cover the remaining area we can use 2 function : calc and fr. To use calc we will write the command as grid-templatte-columns: 100px 3em 40% calc(100% - 40% - 100px - 3em);. Now to use fr (fractional unit), writing 1fr covers up the whole remaining free space. so if we write the command grid-templatte-columns: 100px 3em 40% 1fr; then the last column will have the whole remaining space. If we write grid-templatte-columns: 100px 3em 40% 1fr 2fr; then the remaining space is divided into 3 parts and the last second column is 1/3rd of that space and last column is 2/3rd of that space.
12) In CSS, "em" is a relative unit of measurement for length that is based on the font size of the element. Specifically, 1em is equal to the size of a capital "M" in pixels on a screen, typically set to 16 pixels by default. This means that if an element's font size is set to 16px, then 1em = 16px. The "em" unit is useful for creating scalable layouts, as it adjusts automatically when the font size changes across different devices or screen sizes.
